1 Recommendation/Insight

This report examines factors associated with high rental prices. Our findings show that international students, and those living nearby or working longer hours, tend to pay more. As higher rent is linked to poorer mental health (Bentley et al., 2011), targeted strategies like subsidies and referrals to housing support services may benefit USYD students.

2 Evidence

2.1 IDA

2.1.1 Source

The dataset originates from a student survey conducted in S1, 2025, for the DATA1X01 unit at USYD.

2.1.2 Structure

The dataset comprises 2,145 responses across 28 variables.

The key variables analysed in this report are:

  • Commute (quantitative continuous): Travel time to campus in minutes.

  • Rent (quantitative continuous): Weekly rent in AUD.

  • Student Type (qualitative nominal): Categorised as Domestic (60.8%) or International (39.2%).

  • Hours Worked (quantitative continuous): Number of paid work hours in the past week.

2.1.3 Limitations

Several factors may affect data reliability:

  • Self-reported responses can be biased, especially for subjective measures like stress, which may lack clear criteria.

  • Outliers. Removing them may compromise data completeness.

2.1.4 Assumptions

This analysis is based on the following assumptions:

  • Participants responded honestly and accurately.

  • The sample is representative of the broader student population.

2.1.5 Data cleaning

The dataset was prepared as follows:

  • 42 non-consenting responses were removed, as they provided no relevant insights.

  • Outliersâsuch as physically impossible values for hours workedâwere removed.

  • Outliers beyond three standard deviations were minimalâ1.19% for commute time, 0.9% for rent, and 0.76% for working hoursâand are unlikely to compromise the integrity of the analysis.

  • Student type was coded as a factor for analysis and modeling.

  • All of our key variables had complete data.

2.2 Research Question 1

How does rent vary by DATA 1X01 student enrollment type?

Comparative box plots and kernel density estimates were used to examine rent distribution among DATA1X01 students.

  • All Students
  • Paying Students

The results reveal clear disparities. While 81.9% of domestic students pay no rentâlikely due to living with familyâonly 13.6% of international students do the same. This suggests international students are far more burdened by rental costs.

Among rent-payers, the median weekly rent is $550 for international students and $380 for domestic students. On average, international students pay $517.40 per week, compared to $82.95 for domestic studentsâa 524% increase.

  • Domestic Students
  • International Students

From the Q-Q plot, it is evident that the data are not normally distributed. Thus, we applied a Wilcoxon rank-sum test (p < 0.001), which confirmed a statistically significant rent gap ranging from $403 to $465 per week.

This disparity reflects broader structural barriers; one contributing factor is that, lacking recognised rental history or credit, many international students are priced out of the private market and pushed into compact, overpriced accommodation (Soong & Mu, 2025).

2.3 Research Question 2 (Linear Model)

How is weekly rent associated with commute length to campus and hours worked last week among DATA1X01 students?

We initially assumed a linear relationship between commute time, hours worked, and weekly rent.

The multiple linear regression model:

\text{Rent} = 452.9 - 4.75 \times \text{Commute} + 1.93 \times \text{Hours Worked}

  • RÂ² = 0.1578: About 15.78% of the variation in rent is explained.
  • VIF (~1.004): Negligible multicollinearity.

The â4.75 coefficient suggests students living closer to campus tend to pay higher rent. The 1.93 coefficient indicates a small positive association between hours worked and rentâstudents working longer hours generally pay slightly more, though the effect is limited.

However, the Residuals vs.Â Fitted plot reveals a clear slope, driven by extreme values that, while not genuine outliers, reflect underlying skewness in the data. Consequently, heteroscedasticity and non-linearity emerge, raising concerns about the suitability of a linear modeling approach.

  • Residuals vs.Â Fitted
  • Normal QQ-Plot
  • Scale-Location Plot

Since over half the students (1,152 of 2,089) report zero rent, we transitioned to a two-part model. For rent-paying students (n = 937), an exponential model was applied:
\log(\text{Rent}) = 6.2556 - 0.0038 \times \text{Commute} + 0.0014 \times \text{Hours Worked}

Though the improvement is modest (RÂ² = 0.0151), the model better handles non-linearity and zero inflation.

Overall, the rentâcommuteâwork relationship is more complex than a linear model can capture. Future analysis should explore richer covariates and more flexible modeling strategies.

# Recommendation/Insight

This report examines factors associated with high rental prices. Our findings show that international students, and those living nearby or working longer hours, tend to pay more. As higher rent is linked to poorer mental health (Bentley et al., 2011), targeted strategies like subsidies and referrals to housing support services may benefit USYD students.

# Evidence

## IDA
```{r, warning = FALSE, message = FALSE}
library(tidyverse) 
library(ggplot2)   
library(knitr) 
library(gridExtra)

survey_data <- read.csv("data1001_survey_data_2025_S1.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

dim_data <- dim(survey_data)

consenting_data <- survey_data %>% 
  filter(consent == "I consent to take part in the study")

missing_values <- consenting_data %>% 
  summarise(
    missing_rent = sum(is.na(rent)),
    missing_student_type = sum(is.na(student_type)),
    missing_commute = sum(is.na(commute))
  )

rent_summary <- consenting_data %>% 
  summarise(
    min = min(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    q1 = quantile(rent, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE),
    median = median(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean = mean(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    q3 = quantile(rent, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    max = max(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd = sd(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  )

rent_iqr <- as.numeric(rent_summary$q3 - rent_summary$q1) 
rent_lower_bound <- as.numeric(rent_summary$q1 - 1.5 * rent_iqr)
rent_upper_bound <- as.numeric(rent_summary$q3 + 1.5 * rent_iqr)

rent_outliers <- consenting_data %>%
  filter(rent < rent_lower_bound | rent > rent_upper_bound)

commute_summary <- consenting_data %>% 
  summarise(
    min = min(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    q1 = quantile(commute, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE),
    median = median(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean = mean(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    q3 = quantile(commute, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    max = max(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd = sd(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  )

commute_iqr <- as.numeric(commute_summary$q3 - commute_summary$q1) 
commute_lower_bound <- as.numeric(commute_summary$q1 - 1.5 * commute_iqr)
commute_upper_bound <- as.numeric(commute_summary$q3 + 1.5 * commute_iqr)

commute_outliers <- consenting_data %>%
  filter(commute < commute_lower_bound | commute > commute_upper_bound)

consenting_data$student_type <- as.factor(consenting_data$student_type) 

student_type_dist <- consenting_data %>% 
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = round(count / sum(count) * 100, 2))

rent_by_student_type <- consenting_data %>% 
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    mean_rent = mean(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_rent = median(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_rent = min(rent, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_rent = max(rent, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

commute_by_student_type <- consenting_data %>% 
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    mean_commute = mean(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_commute = median(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    min_commute = min(commute, na.rm = TRUE),
    max_commute = max(commute, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
```

## Research Question 1

**How does rent vary by DATA 1X01 student enrollment type?**

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
options(warn = -1)
suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(tidyverse)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(knitr)
  library(scales)
  library(car)
})
options(warn = 0)

survey_data <- read.csv("data1001_survey_data_2025_S1.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

consenting_data <- survey_data %>%
  filter(consent == "I consent to take part in the study")

consenting_data$student_type <- factor(consenting_data$student_type)

data_clean <- consenting_data %>%
  dplyr::select(student_type, rent) %>%
  filter(!is.na(student_type), !is.na(rent))

data_clean <- data_clean %>%
  mutate(rent_category = case_when(
    rent == 0 ~ "No Rent",
    rent > 0 & rent <= 200 ~ "$1-$200",
    rent > 200 & rent <= 400 ~ "$201-$400",
    rent > 400 & rent <= 600 ~ "$401-$600",
    rent > 600 & rent <= 800 ~ "$601-$800",
    rent > 800 & rent <= 1000 ~ "$801-$1000",
    rent > 1000 ~ "Over $1000"
  ))

data_clean$rent_category <- factor(data_clean$rent_category,
                                   levels = c("No Rent", "$1-$200", "$201-$400", "$401-$600",
                                             "$601-$800", "$801-$1000", "Over $1000"))

rent_summary <- data_clean %>%
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarize(
    n = n(),
    zeros = sum(rent == 0),
    zeros_pct = round(mean(rent == 0) * 100, 1),
    mean_all = round(mean(rent), 2),
    median_all = median(rent),
    sd_all = round(sd(rent), 2),
    min_all = min(rent),
    max_all = max(rent),
    q1_all = quantile(rent, 0.25),
    q3_all = quantile(rent, 0.75),
    iqr_all = IQR(rent),
    n_paying = sum(rent > 0),
    pct_paying = round(mean(rent > 0) * 100, 1),
    mean_paying = round(mean(rent[rent > 0]), 2),
    median_paying = median(rent[rent > 0]),
    sd_paying = round(sd(rent[rent > 0]), 2),
    min_paying = min(rent[rent > 0]),
    max_paying = max(rent[rent > 0])
  )

rent_dist <- data_clean %>%
  group_by(student_type, rent_category) %>%
  summarize(
    count = n(),
    .groups = 'drop'
  ) %>%
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  mutate(
    pct = round(count / sum(count) * 100, 1)
  )

wilcox_test_all <- wilcox.test(rent ~ student_type, data = data_clean)

wilcox_test_paying <- wilcox.test(rent ~ student_type, data = data_clean %>% filter(rent > 0))

data_with_ranks <- data_clean %>%
  mutate(rent_rank = rank(rent))

rank_biserial_all <- data_with_ranks %>%
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarize(mean_rank = mean(rent_rank)) %>%
  {(.$mean_rank[2] - .$mean_rank[1]) / n_distinct(data_with_ranks$rent_rank)}

rank_biserial_paying <- data_with_ranks %>%
  filter(rent > 0) %>%
  group_by(student_type) %>%
  summarize(mean_rank = mean(rent_rank)) %>%
  {(.$mean_rank[2] - .$mean_rank[1]) / n_distinct(data_with_ranks$rent_rank[data_with_ranks$rent > 0])}
```

knitr::asis_output("Comparative box plots and kernel density estimates were used to examine rent distribution among DATA1X01 students.")

kde_all <- ggplot(data_clean, aes(x = rent, fill = student_type)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"), 
                    limits = c(0, 1500)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Domestic" = "#0088FE", "International" = "#00C49F")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Kernel Density Estimation of Rent Distribution",
       subtitle = "All Students",
       x = "Weekly Rent (AUD)",
       y = "Density",
       fill = "Student Type") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        text = element_text(size = 12))

print(kde_all)

boxplot_paying <- data_clean %>%
  filter(rent > 0) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = student_type, y = rent)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "skyblue", color = "navy", alpha = 0.7) +
  stat_summary(fun = median, geom = "point", shape = 18, size = 3, color = "red") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar_format(prefix = "$"), 
                    limits = c(0, 1500)) +  # Limit y-axis to exclude extreme outliers
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Rent vs. Student Type: Paying Students Only",
       subtitle = paste0("Domestic (n=", rent_summary$n_paying[1], ") vs International (n=", rent_summary$n_paying[2], ")"),
       x = "Student Type",
       y = "Weekly Rent (AUD)",
       caption = "Note: Only includes students who pay rent (rent > 0). Red diamonds show medians.") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        text = element_text(size = 12)) +
  # Add median annotations
  annotate("text", 
           x = c(1, 2), 
           y = c(
             median(data_clean$rent[data_clean$student_type == "Domestic" & data_clean$rent > 0]) + 50,
             median(data_clean$rent[data_clean$student_type == "International" & data_clean$rent > 0]) + 50
           ), 
           label = c(
             paste0("$", median(data_clean$rent[data_clean$student_type == "Domestic" & data_clean$rent > 0])),
             paste0("$", median(data_clean$rent[data_clean$student_type == "International" & data_clean$rent > 0]))
           ),
           color = "red",
           size = 4)

print(boxplot_paying)

```{r}
knitr::asis_output("From the Q-Q plot, it is evident that the data are not normally distributed. Thus, we applied a Wilcoxon rank-sum test (p < 0.001), which confirmed a statistically significant rent gap ranging from $403 to $465 per week.

This disparity reflects broader structural barriers; one contributing factor is that, lacking recognised rental history or credit, many international students are priced out of the private market and pushed into compact, overpriced accommodation (Soong & Mu, 2025).")
```

## Research Question 2 (Linear Model)

**How is weekly rent associated with commute length to campus and hours worked last week among DATA1X01 students?**

```{r}
options(warn = -1)
options(message = FALSE)

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(tidyverse)
  library(car)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(gridExtra)
  library(ggpubr)
  library(MASS)
  library(pscl)
})

survey_data <- read.csv("data1001_survey_data_2025_S1.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

consenting_data <- survey_data %>%
  filter(consent == "I consent to take part in the study")

commute_mean <- mean(consenting_data$commute, na.rm = TRUE)
commute_sd <- sd(consenting_data$commute, na.rm = TRUE)
hours_work_mean <- mean(consenting_data$hours_work, na.rm = TRUE)
hours_work_sd <- sd(consenting_data$hours_work, na.rm = TRUE)

filtered_data <- consenting_data %>%
  filter(
    (commute <= commute_mean + 3*commute_sd | is.na(commute)),
    (commute >= commute_mean - 3*commute_sd | is.na(commute)),
    (hours_work <= hours_work_mean + 3*hours_work_sd | is.na(hours_work)),
    (hours_work >= hours_work_mean - 3*hours_work_sd | is.na(hours_work)),
    !is.na(commute),
    !is.na(hours_work),
    !is.na(rent)
  )

regression_data <- filtered_data %>%
  dplyr::select(rent, commute, hours_work)

regression_data$commute_std <- scale(regression_data$commute)
regression_data$hours_work_std <- scale(regression_data$hours_work)

invisible(summary(regression_data))

cor_matrix <- cor(regression_data[, c("rent", "commute", "hours_work")])

model1 <- lm(rent ~ commute + hours_work, data = regression_data)
invisible(summary(model1))

vif_values <- vif(model1)

model2 <- lm(rent ~ commute_std + hours_work_std, data = regression_data)
invisible(summary(model2))

r_value <- sqrt(summary(model1)$r.squared)
r_squared <- summary(model1)$r.squared
adj_r_squared <- summary(model1)$adj.r.squared

residuals <- residuals(model1)
fitted_values <- fitted(model1)

filtered_data$pays_rent <- as.factor(ifelse(filtered_data$rent > 0, "Yes", "No"))

zero_rent_students <- filtered_data %>% 
  filter(rent == 0)
mean_commute_zero_rent <- mean(zero_rent_students$commute, na.rm = TRUE)

rent_paying_students <- filtered_data %>% 
  filter(rent > 0)

rent_paying_students$log_rent <- log(rent_paying_students$rent)

exp_model <- lm(log_rent ~ commute + hours_work, data = rent_paying_students)
invisible(summary(exp_model))

linear_model <- lm(rent ~ commute + hours_work, data = rent_paying_students)
invisible(summary(linear_model))

rent_paying_students$pred_rent <- exp(predict(exp_model))

model3 <- lm(rent ~ commute * hours_work, data = regression_data)
invisible(summary(model3))
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
knitr::asis_output("We initially assumed a linear relationship between commute time, hours worked, and weekly rent. 

The multiple linear regression model:

$$\\text{Rent} = 452.9 - 4.75 \\times \\text{Commute} + 1.93 \\times \\text{Hours Worked}$$

* RÂ² = 0.1578: About 15.78% of the variation in rent is explained.  
* VIF (~1.004): Negligible multicollinearity.")
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
#| warning: false
p3 <- ggplot(regression_data, aes(x = commute, y = hours_work, color = rent)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "green", high = "red") +
  labs(title = "Rent by Commute Time and Hours Worked",
       x = "Commute Time (minutes)",
       y = "Hours Worked Last Week",
       color = "Weekly Rent (AUD)") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p3)
```

```{r}
#| echo: false
knitr::asis_output("The â4.75 coefficient suggests students living closer to campus tend to pay higher rent. The 1.93 coefficient indicates a small positive association between hours worked and rentâstudents working longer hours generally pay slightly more, though the effect is limited.

However, the Residuals vs. Fitted plot reveals a clear slope, driven by extreme values that, while not genuine outliers, reflect underlying skewness in the data. Consequently, heteroscedasticity and non-linearity emerge, raising concerns about the suitability of a linear modeling approach.
")
```

## Residuals vs. Fitted

#| echo: false
#| warning: false
residuals <- residuals(model1)
fitted_values <- fitted(model1)

p4 <- ggplot(data.frame(fitted = fitted_values, residuals = residuals), 
            aes(x = fitted, y = residuals)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "blue", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values",
       x = "Fitted Values",
       y = "Residuals") +
  theme_minimal()

  stat_qq() +
  stat_qq_line(color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Normal QQ-Plot of Residuals",
       x = "Theoretical Quantiles",
       y = "Sample Quantiles") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p5)

p6 <- ggplot(data.frame(fitted = fitted_values, 
                        sqrt_abs_residuals = sqrt(abs(residuals))), 
             aes(x = fitted, y = sqrt_abs_residuals)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "blue", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Scale-Location Plot",
       x = "Fitted Values",
       y = "â|Standardized Residuals|") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p6)
